echo '<div class="mk-prose">';
echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">Tradition keepers, elders, titled men and women, and cultural custodians who preserved and transmitted Igbo tradition.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Role of Elders — Ndị Okenye</h2>';
echo '<p>In Igbo tradition, the elder (okenye) is not simply an old person — they are the repository of communal memory, the link between the living and the ancestors, and the primary authority in matters of tradition. Elders adjudicate disputes, bless ceremonies, interpret traditional law, and correct deviations from established practice. Their authority is earned through long life, demonstrated character, and formal recognition by the community.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Dibia — Keeper of Sacred Knowledge</h2>';
echo '<p>The dibia is the specialist in sacred knowledge — divination, medicine, masquerade, and the negotiation of relationships between the human and spirit worlds. The dibia\'s knowledge is the most specialized form of traditional expertise, transmitted through apprenticeship and initiation. The dibia does not volunteer their services; they are sought out by those in need.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Titled Man — Ọzọ / Nze</h2>';
echo '<p>The titled man in Igbo tradition is the closest equivalent to the "citizen" in the Greek polis — someone who has earned the right to a voice in community governance through demonstrated virtue, wealth, and community support. The Ọzọ title in particular is the marker of full adult male status in many Igbo communities.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Titled Woman — Lolo / Ọzọ Ụmụokpara</h2>';
echo '<p>Women\'s title systems in Igbo tradition are less well-documented but equally important. Titled women (Lolo, and in some communities women\'s Ọzọ) have earned public recognition for their character, generosity, and community service. The ụmụada institution gives all women of the lineage a formal communal role regardless of title.</p>';
echo '<h2>Contemporary Tradition Keepers</h2>';
echo '<p>Today Igbo tradition is kept alive by a combination of community elders, cultural organizations (Ohanaeze Ndigbo, Ọzọ title holders\' associations, masquerade societies), scholars (University of Nigeria Nsukka\'s Igbo Studies department), and diaspora communities who organize cultural festivals, language schools, and community events. The challenge of tradition in the diaspora — maintaining living practice when separated from the land, community, and seasonal cycle that gives it meaning — is one of the defining challenges of Igbo life in the 21st century.</p>';
